A COMPLETELY SERIOUS INVESTIGATION INTO THE GENERAL DIRECTION, INTENTIONS, AND DESSERT PREFERENCES OF GRAVITY

Abstract  
Gravity is widely accepted to be responsible for falling, orbits, and several minor inconveniences. However, its true nature remains unclear. In this paper we review the leading theories of gravity, including force, spacetime curvature, acceleration, entropy, geometry, and ice cream. We present new experimental results based on dropping various office supplies and conclude that gravity is almost certainly doing something, although further work is required to determine what.

1. Introduction  
Gravity has been studied for several hundred years, primarily by dropping things and writing down what happened. Despite this, the scientific community remains divided on what gravity actually is. Some believe it is a force, others believe it is curved spacetime, and a small but growing group believe it is a funding strategy.  
The purpose of this paper is to finally determine what gravity is, or at the very least produce a document that looks like we tried.

2. Gravity as Acceleration  
It has been established that gravity is acceleration.  
This is an extremely important discovery and explains a great deal.  
However, this is also everything we know about that, so we will move on.

3. Current Theories of Gravity  

3.1 Gravity as a Force  
First proposed by a man sitting under a tree who was attacked by fruit, gravity was described as a force that attracts objects to each other. This theory worked extremely well until people started asking more complicated questions.

3.2 Gravity as Curved Spacetime  
Einstein later proposed that gravity is not a force but the result of spacetime being curved. This raised further questions, such as:  
- What is spacetime made of?  
- What is it curved into?  
- Is it possible it is just slightly bent and nobody noticed?

3.3 Gravity as a Wave  
More recently, gravity has been detected as waves. This suggests gravity may be a ripple. If this is the case, we are currently experiencing the middle of a ripple, which raises the important question: where is the end of the wave? We propose it may be slightly to the left.

3.4 Gravity as Geometry  
At this point, most physicists agree gravity is probably geometry. Unfortunately, nobody is entirely sure what this means, but it involves tensors, which are very serious.

4. Gravity and Entropy  
Some scientists believe gravity is related to entropy, which is always increasing. This would explain why everything becomes more messy over time and why drawers that were tidy in 2014 are no longer tidy now.  
It may also explain black holes. Black holes are said to have infinite density, which is a very large amount of density and therefore probably requires a lot of entropy. This is consistent with the fact that entropy is always increasing and black holes are widely known to be extremely serious.  
We attempted to test this theory by increasing the entropy in the office kitchen, but this did not produce a black hole, only a meeting.

5. Black Holes and Spaghettification  
In order to better understand gravity, it was proposed that a member of staff be lowered into a black hole to see what happens. Alison from HR was nominated due to her strong email presence, but she declined on health and safety grounds and also because she said “absolutely not.”  
This is unfortunate as it would have answered several questions and potentially cancelled the Tuesday team-building exercises.

6. The Personality of Gravity  
What we can say with 100% scientific certainty is that gravity can one day be your friend and the next your worst enemy. For example:  
- It keeps you on the ground.  
- It also makes you fall off ladders.  
This suggests gravity may hold grudges or at the very least has a complicated relationship with humans.  
Because revenge is a dish best served cold, we cannot rule out the possibility that gravity is, in fact, ice cream. Further research is required into which flavour.

7. Experimental Results  
We performed a series of high-precision experiments:

Object Dropped | Result  
----------------|--------  
Pen | Fell  
Mug | Fell  
Important document | Fell  
Morale | Fell  

All results were statistically significant.

8. Discussion  
At this stage, gravity appears to be:  
- A force  
- Acceleration  
- Curved spacetime  
- Entropy  
- Geometry  
- Possibly ice cream  
- Or some combination of the above  
This places gravity in the category of “complicated.”

9. Field Research: The Ice Cream Man  
In order to investigate the previously proposed hypothesis that gravity may in fact be ice cream, we conducted field research with a local ice cream vendor.  
When asked about gravity, the ice cream man stated that a 99 with a flake now costs £7.99 and does not include a flake. This represents a significant increase compared to previous years and also a significant decrease in flake.  
This observation is of great scientific importance because it demonstrates three key phenomena:

Phenomenon | Behaviour  
-----------|-----------  
Gravity | Pulls things down  
Entropy | Always increases  
Price of a 99 | Always increases  

Furthermore, the amount of flake appears to be decreasing, which suggests the existence of an additional physical law known as Flake Conservation Failure.  
This leads to the following unified theory:  
As entropy increases, flakes decrease, prices increase, and gravity continues to behave however it wants.  
This is the first time these three quantities have been linked in a single theoretical framework and represents a major breakthrough in dessert-based physics.

10. Economic Model of Gravity  
We propose that gravity may operate on a supply and demand basis. There is a high demand for “down,” and gravity continues to supply it.  
Attempts to supply “up” have been largely unsuccessful except in balloons, rockets, and very small dogs that jump too high.

11. Proposed Grand Unified Theory  
We therefore propose the following possibilities for what gravity actually is:  
1. A force  
2. Acceleration  
3. Curved spacetime  
4. Entropy  
5. Geometry  
6. Ice cream  
7. The price of a 99  
8. A management strategy  
9. Something to do with magnets (unlikely but worth mentioning)  
10. Bigfoot  
At this stage, Bigfoot explains almost as many things as quantum gravity, and significantly more than our current budget.

12. Future Work  
Future research should focus on:  
- Looking at gravity from the side  
- Increasing the flake budget  
- Sending someone who is not Alison from HR into a black hole  
- Measuring whether gravity behaves differently on Wednesdays  
- Applying for funding and being rejected  
- Building a machine that turns gravity off briefly to see what happens

13. Conclusion  
In conclusion, gravity is definitely present and continues to operate in a downward direction with malicious consistency. However, until the price of a 99 stops increasing and flakes are restored to their natural levels, we cannot rule out the possibility that gravity, entropy, and ice cream are all part of the same system.  
This system is complicated and may be run by someone else.

